\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, two stochastic information spread models are presented: a traditional information spread ISI model and an ISR information model, specifically tailored to social media information. Like other information spread models, these models are adapted from mathematical epidemiology models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "allen2008mathematical"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 with special consideration paid to the naming conventions of variables, a negligible birth and death rate over the short time it takes to spread information, and state transition differences due to human social media behavior. The same general principles presented here for the ISI and ISR models can be applied to other information spread models to achieve their coinciding stochastic model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stochastic ISI Information Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that in the Ignorant-Spreader-Ignorant model, the ignorant class learns and gains interest in a topic, spreads the information to others until said information becomes old or boring, and then returns to the ignorant state until the same topic or family of topics has new and interesting information available to learn to rekindle a desire to spread again. The stochastic ISI model is no different in concept, but must be handled differently due to the probabilistic nature of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the expanded ISI deterministic system, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N=I+S$
\end_inset

 as the total population (for simplicity, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 can be set to 1 to simulate a population percentage as is done elsewhere in this paper). For ease of understanding, classes are generally displayed without time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 unless required, though they remain a function of time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The system dynamics of the IS model are taken to be: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eqn:ISI_dynamics_2}
\left.\begin{aligned}
\dot{i} = -\frac{\beta}{N} i s+\gamma s\\
\dot{s} = \frac{\beta}{N} i s-\gamma s
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Now, let us examine the following Itô SDE: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eqn:Ito_ISI}
\left.\begin{aligned}
\frac{dS}{dt}= \mu(S) + \sigma(S) \frac{dW}{dt},
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the Wiener process. If Euler's method is utilized, the system model converges to the Itô SDE if specific growth and smoothness conditions are met, just as in stochastic epidemic models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "allen2008mathematical"
literal "true"

\end_inset

. For this ISI model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(S)=b(S)-d(S)$
\end_inset

 is the deterministic growth and decay of the information as before, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(S)=\sqrt{b(S)+d(S)}$
\end_inset

 is the stochastic element of the system, where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eqn:Ito_coeff}
\left.\begin{aligned}
b(S) = \frac{\beta}{N} S(N-S) \nonumber \\
d(S)= \gamma S. \nonumber
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

By expressing the dynamics in terms of the spreader class and making the above substitutions into the Itô SDE, the stochastic ISI information spread model can be obtained in the form of the following SDE: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eqn:ISI_SDE}
\left.\begin{aligned}
\frac{dS}{dt} = \frac{\beta}{N} S(N-S)- \gamma S + \sqrt{\frac{\beta}{N} S(N-S)+\gamma S} \frac{dW}{dt}.
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

