\begin_layout Section
Stochastic ISR Information Model and Social Media Spread
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Just as with the stochastic ISI model, similar assumptions and processes can be applied to the ISR information spread model, given a reasonably normal distribution for random variables. Two cases of the ISR information spread model are explored here: traditional and social media.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the traditional model, the ignorant class learns and hears about new information from traditional media and social sources such as word-of-mouth, newspaper articles, and television. These methods of contact are reasonably quick, so birth and death rates of analogous epidemic models are negligible and subsequently omitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta X(t)=(\Delta I, \Delta S)^T$
\end_inset

, its expectation can be expressed as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eqn:ISR_Exp}
E(\Delta X(t))=
\begin{bmatrix}
   -\frac{\beta}{N}IS \\
   \frac{\beta}{N}IS - \gamma S[S+R]
\end{bmatrix}
\Delta t. \nonumber
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Next, the covariance matrix can be determined using the expectation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left.\begin{aligned}
V(\Delta X(t))= E(\Delta X(t)[\Delta X(t)]^T)-E(\Delta X(t))E(\Delta X(t))^T) \\
V(\Delta X(t)) \approx E(\Delta X(t)[\Delta X(t)]^T) \\
V(\Delta X(t))=
\begin{bmatrix}
   \frac{\beta}{N}IS &
   -\frac{\beta}{N}IS \\
   -\frac{\beta}{N}IS &
   \frac{\beta}{N}IS+\gamma S 
\end{bmatrix}
\Delta t. \nonumber
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Note that the covariance matrix is both positive definite and symmetric with square root 
\begin_inset Formula $B\sqrt{\Delta t}=\sqrt{V}$
\end_inset

. Approximating the random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t+\Delta t)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
X(t+\Delta t)=X(t)+\Delta X(t) \approx X(t)+E(\Delta X(t))+\sqrt{V(\Delta X(t))}.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

This is an Euler approximation to a system of Itô standard differential equations and assuming reasonably smooth coefficients, the solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left.\begin{aligned}
\frac{dI}{dt}=-\frac{\beta}{N}IS+B_{11}\frac{dW_1}{dt}+B_{12}\frac{dW_2}{dt} \\
\frac{dS}{dt}=\frac{\beta}{N}IS-\gamma S+B_{21}\frac{dW_1}{dt}+B_{22}\frac{dW_2}{dt},
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_2$
\end_inset

 are independent Wiener processes and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the intensity of fluctuations based on the environment (population and network profile in this case) 
